# Frontend: Angular

## Project Structure
- Use feature modules: group components, services, and routes by feature
- Use a `shared/` module for reusable components, pipes, and directives
- Use a `core/` module for singleton services (auth, HTTP interceptors, guards)
- Lazy-load feature modules via router for performance

## Components
- Use standalone components (Angular 14+) for new code; migrate modules gradually
- Use `OnPush` change detection strategy by default
- Keep components focused — delegate logic to services
- Use `input()` and `output()` signal-based APIs (Angular 17+) where possible
- Prefix component selectors with the app or feature name: `app-order-list`

## Services
- Use `providedIn: 'root'` for singleton services
- Use `inject()` function over constructor injection in standalone components
- Keep HTTP calls in dedicated service classes; never call `HttpClient` from components
- Handle errors in services; expose clean observables or signals to components

## State Management
- Use Angular Signals for local component state (Angular 16+)
- Use NgRx or NGXS for complex global state with clear actions and reducers
- Use RxJS operators for async data transformations
- Avoid storing derived state — compute it

## Routing
- Use lazy loading for all feature routes
- Use route guards for authentication and authorization
- Use route resolvers for pre-fetching data
- Define routes in a `*.routes.ts` file per feature

## Testing
- Use `TestBed` for component and service tests
- Use `spectator` or `testing-library/angular` for simpler component tests
- Mock HTTP calls with `HttpClientTestingModule`
- Test components in isolation; mock child components

## Conventions
- Follow the Angular Style Guide (angular.io/guide/styleguide)
- Use `ng lint` with `eslint` in CI
- Use `trackBy` in `*ngFor` / `@for` for list performance
- Use `async` pipe or `toSignal()` to auto-unsubscribe from observables
